    d.
        Human blood cells are shaped as biconcave disks to increase surface area. A higher surface area means more area for haemoglobin to bind with oxygen, so more oxygen can be taken around the body at a higher rate, so oxygen transfer is more efficient. The volume of red blood cells is limited by capillary size, and so the red blood cells cannot get bigger to compensate for the lower surface area to volume ratio (a sphere has the lowest possible surface area to volume ratio), so less oxygen will be transported per unit time, so efficiency of oxygen transport will be reduced, possibly leading to not enough oxygen reaching cells.
