    b.
        i.
            Concentration of carbon dioxide
        ii.
            Volume of water supplied to the wheat plants
            control light intensity: keep the light intensity supplied to all plants the same at all times
        iii.
            let area of each area = a =  pi * (0.4)^2
            ((68/a) + (72/a) + (66/a) + (75/a) + (76/a) + (63/a))/6 = (68 + 72 + 66 + 75 + 76 + 63)/(6 * pi * (0.4)^2)
            = 139.260575205
            ~= 139 stomata per mm^2
        iv.
            The investigation did not vary the temperature or the humidity of the plants. So, it cannot be directly concluded that in hot dry areas, with increased carbon dioxide, it is an advantage for wheat to have a lower mean density of stomata. Further, the experiment only showed that increased carbon dioxide leads to a lower mean density of stomata; the final mass etc of wheat were not measured, so it is not directly clear that a lower mean density of stomata is advantageous. However, the scientist is likely correct in saying this, as a lower mean density of stomata will lead to a lower rate of transpiration as there will be less gas flow through the leaves as there will be less stomata per mm^2 and so less diffusion of water out of the leaf. In a hot and dry area, the heat already increases the rate of transpiration as evaporation is faster when temperature is high; further, dry means the air will be dryer so there will be a higher concentration gradient so the rate of diffusion will also be higher; dry also means the plant may struggle to get enough water from the soil to replenish lost water. So, less stomata to reduce the rate of loss of water is likely beneficial. Further, plants generally grow in beneficial ways, so since in a high concentration of carbon dioxide the wheat plants developed a lower mean density of stomata, it is likely beneficial; in addition, high concentration of carbon dioxide means a lower rate of airflow through the plant's leaves will still provide the same amount of carbon dioxide as the concentration gradient will be higher so faster diffusion occurs and so more carbon dioxide can be extracted per unit volume of air as the concentration gradient will be higher for longer. This means that not as many stomata is necessary to take in enough carbon dioxide for photosynthesis, so therefore for the aforementioned reason, and because water is also necessary to prevent plasmolysis and also necessary for photosynthesis which produces glucose for respiration and energy, it would likely be an advatnage for wheat to have a lower mean density of stomata.
4.
    a.
        Selective breeding can be used to produce fish that grow rapidly by breeding together fish which grew rapidly, and then breeding together the fastest-growing fish of their offspring, and so on, over many generations.
    b?
        Ammonia is converted into nitrates by nitrifying bacteria which may live in the roots of plants or in the water.
    c.
        A multi-trophic aquaculture system reduces environmental pollution as follows:
        - Normally, minerals and nitrates produced as a result of the fish excrement, wasted as a result of putting too much in the water, by putting growth hormone in the water etc, would disperse and lead to eutrophication, death of underwater plants, aquatic life etc. However, since there is seaweed growing on a nearby platform, it can absorb much of these minerals and nitrates etc and prevent it from dispersing uncontrollably. Further, the grown seaweed can be sold to increase revenue of the fish farm.
        - Normally, waste food and faeces would go to waste, or would also decompose into ammonia or nitrate and eutrophication would occur as a result. Also, they would in general pollute the sea and the environment. Here, however, they are consumed by lobsters and crabs as they sink to the sea floor, so they do not disperse and pollute, and also do not go to waste, which is beneficial because feed costs money and faeces is free, and this feeds the lobsters and crabs which, again, can be sold for a profit.
