    c?
        A mutation in a gene will lead to a different mRNA being produced via transcription and then hence a different amino acid being brought by tRNA during translation, and hence in a different sequence of amino acids and then hence a different polypeptide, which will likely fold to form a differently-shaped protein, which changes the shape of its active site so that the original substrates no longer fit, which means the protein will have a different function as original and no longer work in its original capacity, which means the cell's function and characteristics will be impacted, causing a different phenotype. However, if by chance the same amino acid is coded for or if the change in final shape of the protein is not so significant as to mean the original substrates cannot fit, there may be no change in phenotype.
    d.
        i?
            Scientists could have sampled the population of butterflies by using a net or similar apparatus to catch twenty random butterflies of this species (discarding any caught that are not of this species), and then repeating this three times per collection, and taking the mean for percentage of butterflies with abnormalities each time. 
        ii.
            Ten months after the accident, percentages of butterflies with mutations were higher in both adults and in offspring. For both two and ten months after the accident, offspring were more likely to have abnormalities than adults. There is a much greater difference between percentage of offspring with abnormalities vs percentage of adults with abnormalities ten months after the accident (60.2 - 28.1 = 32.1) as opposed to two months (18.3 - 12.4 = 5.9); and, similarly, the increase in percentage for adults (28.1 - 12.4 = 15.7) is much lower than in offspring (60.2 - 18.3 = 41.9). Adults two months after the accident had the least percentage of abnormalities, whereas offspring 10 months after the accident had the most percentage of abnormalities. Offspring likely have a higher percentage of mutation because the parents' gametes are produced via meiosis, which involves two divisions rather than one, so there is a higher chance of mutations there, and the rapid cell division of the butterfly while they are in their eggs/while they are growing up also leads to a higher chance of mutations and hence abnormalities.

            It could be that the increased level of radioactivity has led to an increased rate of mutation of DNA. This is supported by the data, as indeed longer exposure to radiation seems to have led to more mutation. However, we do not know if other factors from the accident or otherwise led to this increase in mutation.
